	<example><title>Verify our solution</title>

		<p>
			<p>
				Verify that
				<me>z = \tan(t+C)</me>
				is the particular solution to the initial value problem
				<me>z' - 1 = z^2, \quad z(4) = 9</me>
			</p>
		</p>
		
		<p>
			<solution>
				<p>
					As in the previous example, we don't have to check our answer, but one of the best parts about DEs is that we always can check, which means we can really know if we have the right solution. Let's check this one. We will substitute our solution back into the DE and verify that when we do, we get the same thing on both sides of the equation.
		
					<md>
						<mrow> LHS	\amp = z' -1</mrow>
						<mrow> \amp = \frac{d}{dt}\Big( \tan(t+C) \Big) - 1</mrow>
						<mrow> \amp = \sec^2(t+C)\cdot \frac{d}{dt}(t+C) - 1</mrow>
						<mrow> \amp = \sec^2(t+C)\cdot (1+0) - 1</mrow>
						<mrow> \amp = \sec^2(t+C) - 1</mrow>
					</md>
		
					<md>
						<mrow> RHS	\amp = z^2</mrow>
						<mrow> \amp = \Big( \tan(t+C) \Big)^2</mrow>
						<mrow> \amp = \tan^2(t+C)</mrow>
					</md>
		
				</p>
		
				<p>
					At first glance, it looks like we have different expressions on the left and right hand sides of the equation. However, if we recall the trigonometric identity
		
						<me>\tan^2 x = \sec^2 x - 1,</me>
		
					then we can see that these expressions are, in fact equivalent. Thus, we have verified that <m>z = \tan(t+C)</m>, where <m>C</m> is any constant, is a solution to the DE <m>z' -1 = z^2</m>.
				</p>
		
				<p>
					Now that we've practiced this solution technique a couple of times, let's summarize.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</p>

	</example>

		<example>
			<title>Algebra Required: Making the Equation Separable</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the general solution to the differential equation:
				</p>
				<me> y^2 y' - 1 = 6x^2 </me>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					This equation is not obviously separable as written, so we begin by solving for <m>y'</m>:
					<md>
						<mrow> y^2 y' \amp = 6x^2 + 1 </mrow>
						<mrow> \frac{dy}{dx} \amp = \frac{6x^2 + 1}{y^2} = \big( 6x^2 + 1 \big)\cdot \left( \frac{1}{y^2} \right) </mrow>
					</md>
					This is now in separable form.
				</p>
				<p>
					We now separate and integrate:
					<md>
						<mrow> y^2 dy \amp = (6x^2 + 1) dx </mrow>
						<mrow> \int y^2 dy \amp = \int (6x^2 + 1) dx </mrow>
						<mrow> \frac{y^3}{3} \amp = 2x^3 + x + c </mrow>
					</md>
					Multiplying through and isolating <m>y</m> gives the general solution:
					<me> y = \sqrt[3]{6x^3 + 3x + c} </me>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>

		<exercise>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Show the differential equations is separable.
				<me>
					t - ss' = - s, \qquad
				</me>
			</p>
		</statement>
		
		<solution><title><term>Isolate the Derivative First</term></title>
			<p>
				To see that this equation is separable, we need to check that it can be rearranged in <xref provisional="separable" text="custom">separable form</xref>. Isolating <m> s' </m> we get
				<me> s' = \frac{s + t}{s} </me>
				and it should be clear that there is no way to separate <m>t</m> and <m>s</m> by <em>multiplication</em> in the numerator, so this equation <em>is not separable</em>.
			</p>
		</solution>
		</exercise>
	</subsection>

	<subsection>
		<title>Solve the Differential Equations</title>

		<exercises>
			<title>Name IT</title>
		
			<exercisegroup cols="2"><title>Separable Form</title>
				<introduction>
					<p>
						Determine whether the given differential equation is separable or not. As demonstrated in the examples, if the equation is separable, use parentheses to explicitly show the separable form.
					</p>
				</introduction>

				<exercise><title><m>\ds \frac{dz}{dt} = \sin(z+t)</m></title>
					<statement/>
					<solution>
						<p>
							<alert>not</alert> separable; there's no way to separate th <m> \ds z </m> an <m> \ds t </m> inside the sine term.
						</p>
					</solution>
					<answer>
						<p>
							<alert>not</alert> separable
						</p>
					</answer>
				</exercise>

				<exercise><title><m>\ds s' = t\ln(s^{2t}) + 8t^2</m></title>
					<statement/>
					<solution>
						<p>
							This doesn't look separable; but if we use a property of logarithms we can re-write as follows.
						<md>
							<mrow>  s'	 \amp =  t\ln(s^{2t}) + 8t^2 </mrow>
							<mrow>  \frac{ds}{dt}	 \amp =  t \cdot 2t\ln(s) + 8t^2 </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  2t^2 \ln(s) + 8t^2 </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \big(t^2\big)\big(2\ln(s) + 8\big) </mrow>
						</md>
						Hence, this DE is <alert>separable</alert>.
						</p>
					</solution>
					<answer>
						<p>
							<alert>separable</alert>
						</p>
					</answer>
				</exercise>

				<exercise><title><m>\ds \frac{dy}{dx} = 2y^3 + y + 4</m></title>
					<statement/>
					<solution>
						<p>
					We can rearrange as follows.
						<md>
							<mrow>  \frac{dy}{dx}	 \amp =  \big(1\big)\big(2y^3 + y + 4\big) </mrow>
						</md>
						Hence, this DE is <alert>separable</alert>.
						</p>
					</solution>
					<answer>
						<p>
							<alert>separable</alert>
						</p>
					</answer>
				</exercise>

				<exercise><title><m>\ds y' - xy = 0</m></title>
					<statement/>
					<solution>
						<p>
					We can rearrange as follows.
						<md>
							<mrow>  y' - xy	 \amp =  0 </mrow>
							<mrow>  y'	 \amp =  \big(x\big)\big(y\big) </mrow>
						</md>
						Hence, this DE is <alert>separable</alert>.
						</p>
					</solution>
					<answer>
						<p>
							<alert>separable</alert>
						</p>
					</answer>
				</exercise>

				<exercise><title><m>\ds y' = x+y</m></title>
					<statement/>
					<solution>
						<p>
							<alert>not</alert> separable; there's no way to separate <m> \ds x </m> and <m> \ds y </m> via multiplication/division
						</p>
					</solution>
					<answer>
						<p>
							<alert>not</alert> separable
						</p>
